INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (694,2,'2014-02-26 21:39:08','2014-02-26 21:39:08','<h3>Philadelphia High School Breakfast Specialist</h3>\nThe fellow will develop programming that will encourage teens to participate in school breakfast, which will not only positively affect overall health and learning of Philadelphia’s youth, but will help them be heard and support healthier school climates.<!--more-->\n\nFellowship Project Goal(s)\nThe fellow will develop programming that will encourage teens to participate in school breakfast, which will not only positively affect overall health and learning of Philadelphia’s youth, but will help them be heard and support healthier school climates.  Increasing school breakfast participation is win-win-win for families, students and schools. Greater use of free breakfast allows families’ limited dollars for other necessities. Students and schools share proven benefits: improved school performance, reduced rates of obesity, lower rates of absence and tardiness, and a reduction in discipline problems, behavioral and psychological problems, and visits to school nurse. We believe our Fellow\'s work on a teen-informed plan to increase participation will be replicable, and therefore have long-term impact for teens throughout the district.   \n \nAgency Information\n\nWebsite  www.pccy.org     \n\nAgency Mission  PCCY seeks to improve the lives and life chances of our region’s children through thoughtful and informed advocacy.\n\nAddress  1709 Ben Franklin Parkway, 6th Floor; Philadelphia, PA 19103\n\nTotal number of Agency Staff Members  14\n\nAgency Budget  $1.3 million\n\nCommunity Need\n\n<strong>The specific community need the Philly Fellow will address</strong>\nNearly 65 percent of Philadelphia children live in low-income families. Affording healthy foods is a tremendous challenge. Reliance on low-cost, calorie dense foods contributes to health risks, including child obesity. While obesity rates for SDOP students as a whole have recently decreased, unacceptably high rates of obesity and severe obesity continue to threaten far too many children’s health and futures. This, along with Philadelphia’s high rates of child poverty and food insecurity, makes school breakfast is an incredibly important nutrition and education support for a vast majority of school students. It is available at no cost in all district schools, yet participation lags among high school students. According to data from the School District of Philadelphia Division of Food Services, breakfast participation in K-7 and K-8 schools averaged 46 percent in 2011-12, but high school participation stood at just 27 percent. Furthermore, participation rates among high schools shows tremendous variation. In 2011-12 the ten lowest participation high schools served an average of 15 percent or fewer students each day, while the ten highest participation high schools served an average of 45 percent or more students each day. Based on 2011-12 enrollment figures, the development of strategies to increase breakfast participation among high school students has the potential to improve nutrition habits and support educational achievement of the more than 40,000 teens enrolled in district high schools, as well as help their families stretch their food budgets.\n \n<strong>How the agency addresses this need, and how the new capacity created by this fellow will help alleviate the problem  </strong>      \nPCCY has advocated for District-wide policies to increase participation in school breakfast, but has also learned through our work that targeted efforts at individual schools are also needed to make progress. Teens can provide a wealth of information about current reasons for low participation, as well as effective ideas to improve participation. While PCCY has been an active voice for this issue, a Philly Fellow whose main project goals are focused on school breakfast for high school students would greatly enhance PCCY’s efforts to improve both health and educational outcomes for Philadelphia youth.\n \n<strong>The level of community involvement in the fellow’s project</strong>\nOur Philly Fellow will have extensive interactions with groups of Philadelphia high school students. In the early stages of the project, our Fellow will facilitate focus groups with high school students, as well as perform key informant interviews with other school and food service staff to identify possible barriers to participation as well as begin to collect ideas for improvements. After the initial information gathering, our Fellow will work on a regular basis with a core group of teens from at least three high schools to develop effective strategies to increase participation. The Fellow will facilitate a collaborative process that engages students with various skills and interests, from those with technology or health-focused career goals to those with entrepreneurial or artistic aspirations, to develop strategies to improve participation rates for their schools.\n \n<strong>The agency\'s plan to orient and train the fellow</strong>\nKathy Fisher, our Fellow’s immediate supervisor, will familiarize him/her with the school breakfast program and PCCY’s past work on school meals, as well as introduce him/her to staff of several other anti-hunger and nutrition organizations with whom PCCY works (Greater Philadelphia Coalition Against Hunger, Community Legal Services, The Food Trust, Drexel Center for Hunger-free Communities, The Enterprise Center, and others) so that the Fellow will begin to develop a network of advocates with expertise on different aspects of school food and nutrition issues. PCCY will also explore opportunities for our Fellow to participate in conferences and meetings with other advocates around improving school meals and other anti-hunger efforts.\n \n<strong>Plans for supervision of fellow</strong>\nKathy Fisher, our Fellow’s immediate supervisor, will familiarize him/her with the school breakfast program and PCCY’s past work on school meals, as well as introduce him/her to staff of several other anti-hunger and nutrition organizations with whom PCCY works (Greater Philadelphia Coalition Against Hunger, Community Legal Services, The Food Trust, Drexel Center for Hunger-free Communities, The Enterprise Center, and others) so that the Fellow will begin to develop a network of advocates with expertise on different aspects of school food and nutrition issues. PCCY will also explore opportunities for our Fellow to participate in conferences and meetings with other advocates around improving school meals and other anti-hunger efforts.       ','Public Citizens for Children and Youth','','inherit','open','open','','340-autosave-v1','','','2014-02-26 21:39:08','2014-02-26 21:39:08','',340,'http://phillyfellows.wpengine.com/340-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0);
